---
title: "My journey of studying MERN Stack"
author: Divyansh Washi
vinternship_id: WIN25294R
---

When I first enrolled in a MERN stack course, I’ll be honest — it wasn’t smooth sailing. The concepts felt heavy, unfamiliar, and sometimes overwhelming. On top of that, even navigating the platform where the course was hosted felt like a task in itself. There were moments when I questioned whether I was cut out for this, or if I had taken on more than I could handle.

But something interesting happened with time.

Slowly, almost quietly, things started to make sense. The syntax stopped looking like random symbols. The logic behind the code began to click. What once felt intimidating started feeling… manageable. I didn’t wake up one day as an expert, but I woke up a little more confident than the day before — and that made all the difference.

One thing that genuinely stood out to me was the teaching approach. Instead of long, exhausting videos that make your mind drift and your thumb reach for Instagram, the lessons were broken into short 90–100 second clips. That small design choice had a big impact. It kept me engaged. It reduced mindless doom scrolling. It helped me stay present and actually *learn*, not just watch.

By the time I reached the end of the course, I wasn’t just relieved — I was proud. Proud that I stuck through the confusion. Proud that I adapted. Proud that I finished something that once felt so difficult. And now, knowing that I’ll get to work on real-world projects and case studies, it feels like this was just the beginning, not the end.

This course didn’t just teach me MERN stack development. It taught me patience, consistency, and the value of trusting the process. Sometimes growth doesn’t come with fireworks — it comes quietly, one small clip, one small win at a time. And looking back, I’m really glad I didn’t quit when it felt hard.


